==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/wer/}}

===Etymology 1===
Common Germanic *''werāz'', from Proto-Indo-European ''*wīrō-'' ‘freeman’. Germanic cognates include Old Frisian ''wer'', Old Saxon ''wer'', Old High German ''wer'', Old Norse ''[[verr]]'', Gothic [[𐍅𐌴𐍂]]. The PIE root is also the source of Latin ''[[vir]]'', Old Irish ''[[fer]]'' (Welsh ''[[gwr]]''), Baltic ''*wira-'' (Lithuanian ''[[viras|vīras]]'').

====Noun====
'''wer''' {{m}} (plural '''[[weras]]''')

# [[man]], [[husband]]
# ''(poetic)'' [[hero]]

===Etymology 2===
From ''[[werian]]''.

====Noun====
'''wer''' {{m}} (plural '''[[weras]]''')

# [[weir]]

